=== Ternary Extension: The Plastic Ratio $rho$

The two binary rules examined so far — the mirror and the Fibonacci swinging substitution — operate with two distinct durations only. The swing they articulate is the swing of two elements, long against short, and the infinite words they generate inhabit an alphabet of exactly two letters. Yet certain rhythmic traditions, and certain empirical measurements of traditional grooves, exhibit three distinct durations rather than two. The samba, whose four-element pattern is most accurately modelled as $"MSML"$ — medium, short, medium, long — is the most widely discussed case in the literature.#footnote[Empirical measurements of ternary duration structures have been reported for the samba in "@"2020_Effect_of_tempo_on_relative_note_durations_in_a_performed_samba_groove and related sources; Polak documents analogous three-duration patterns in certain rhythmic traditions from Libya and Mali (see "@"2022_Aesthetics_of_timing). The interpretation proposed in the present section is theoretical rather than ethnomusicological: I take the three-duration character of these patterns as a structural observation and ask what substitution framework accommodates it, without claiming that my framework captures the full musical reality of the traditions concerned. The same caveat stated in Section 3.2.2 applies here.] A theory of fractal rhythm that restricts itself to binary words leaves such patterns unexplained. The present section extends the substitution framework to a ternary alphabet ${S, M, L}$ and shows that a single irrational proportion governs the resulting structures.

The ternary extension can be motivated musically as a _double modulation_ of swing. The argument unfolds in two stages. First, the duplet is swung, producing a long-short configuration $L S$ in the usual way, at some ratio $r_1 = L slash S$. Second, the swung duplet is itself interpreted as a pair of lower-level elements, each of which can carry its own swing. The first half of the duplet — the long $L$ — divides into its own swing pair $L_a S_a$ at ratio $r_2$; the second half — the short $S$ — divides into its own swing pair $S_b L_b$ at the same ratio $r_2$, with opposite groove balance, as the mirror relation demands. The result is a four-element word $L_a S_a S_b L_b$, a quadruplet that is the mirror descendent of the triplet $S L S$, with the inner mirror structure preserved.#footnote[The full derivation — including the coupled equations that emerge when the two ratios $r_1$ and $r_2$ are required to match empirical observations on samba patterns, and the cubic equation whose positive root is the plastic ratio — is the subject of @sec:double-modulation in Book IV.]

