Two observations about the plastic ratio deserve attention here; their full analysis is reserved for Book IV. First, the three durations stand in _geometric progression_, with a common ratio $rho$ — meaning that the rule produces a self-similar structure at every level, with the same proportional relation between consecutive durations regardless of which three consecutive durations one examines. This is a stronger self-similarity than the binary rules can achieve, because the binary case has no intermediate duration; the ternary case is precisely the minimal case in which the progression can be geometric. Second, among all ternary substitutions that can produce self-similar three-duration rhythms under reasonable constraints — dynamical stability, ratio containment below $2$, perceptual viability in the groove window — the Padovan rule and the plastic ratio are _uniquely admissible_. No other ternary rule combines these properties. This uniqueness is a structural fact about the ternary case, not a contingent choice, and it distinguishes the ternary extension from the binary plurality encountered in the preceding sections.#footnote[The uniqueness argument depends on a sharp fact of algebraic number theory — the absence of Pisot numbers between $rho$ and the next Pisot number $psi approx 1.3803$ — which ensures that no alternative ternary substitution satisfies the same constraints at a smaller inflation. See @sec:hierarchy and @sec:synthesis of Book IV for the full development.]

The ternary case therefore consolidates structurally what the binary case leaves distributed. Where the binary alphabet admits multiple admissible rules — the Fibonacci with its golden ratio, the second $sqrt(2)$ rule with its Pisot inflation, the mirror with its non-Pisot compactness — the ternary alphabet admits only the Padovan rule and its plastic ratio. The move from two letters to three is not simply an extension; it is a resolution of the ambiguity present in the binary case, achieved at the cost of introducing a third duration that the binary alphabet could not accommodate.

With the three rules and their three irrational proportions in hand — $sqrt(2)$ for the mirror and its Pisot companion, $phi.alt$ for Fibonacci, $rho$ for Padovan — the task of the next section is to examine how these proportions relate to one another: whether they form a coherent family, what structural properties they share, and what hierarchy they establish in the space of admissible substitution rules.